hopathology by allowing an individual to recognize the need to activate appropriate emotion regulation strategies.<br><br><\\/p><p>Experiments were conducted on seven young people with symptoms of depression. I don\'t want to bother you with unnecessary details so I will cut to two main sections of the experiments. (you can read the whole experiment <a target=\\\"_blank\\\" href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.frontiersin.org\\/articles\\/10.3389\\/fpsyg.2019.01199\\/full\\\" tt-mode=\\\"url\\\">here<\\/a>)<br><br><\\/p><p><br><br><\\/p>\"}', '{\"content\":\"<p><\\/p><img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/digiuth.com\\/uploads\\/digiuth.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\" title=\\\"\\\" tt-mode=\\\"file\\\" tt-link-url=\\\"\\\" tt-link-target=\\\"\\\" tt-link-mode=\\\"url\\\" class=\\\"\\\"><p>Music is such an essential part of every human being\'s livelihood that we could never imagine a world without it. Could you imagine a movie without a score and soundtrack? Surely no. But music isn\'t as easy of a concept as we might think. There\'re many layers and complexities within itself that many scientists have researched and discovered a lot of exciting features. Today I want to touch on several interesting aspects of music that researches uncovered <mark>throughout <\\/mark>the years. Let\'s dive in!<br><br><\\/p><p><br>Mental Health<br><br><\\/p><p>Barry Goldstein, a recording artist who has studied the vibrational effects of music for more than 25 years, says music has a profound impact on the brain. In <a target=\\\"_blank\\\" href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.consciouslifestylemag.com\\/music-and-the-brain-affects-mood\\/\\\" tt-mode=\\\"url\\\">a column<\\/a> for Conscious Lifestyle magazine, Goldstein wrote that music could enhance brain functions. He said music could evoke emotion, help regain memories, stimulate new neural connections, and active attention.<br><br><\\/p><img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/digiuth.com\\/uploads\\/digiuth.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\" title=\\\"\\\" tt-mode=\\\"file\\\" tt-link-url=\\\"\\\" tt-link